msgstr ""

#: https://platform-api.usa.gov:443/api/v1/usagov/narratives/35577.json#summary
msgid "Get employment information for people with disabilities."
msgstr ""

#: https://platform-api.usa.gov:443/api/v1/usagov/narratives/35577.json#html
msgid ""
"<p>If you have a disability and are looking for a job, these resources can "
"help:</p><ul><li><a "
"href=\"http://www.careeronestop.org/ResourcesFor/WorkersWithDisabilities/workers-with-disabilities.aspx\">CareerOneStop.org</a>'s "
"\"Workers with Disabilities\" section&nbsp;provides strategies for developing "
"skills, conducting a job search, and preparing for "
"interviews.</li><li>The&nbsp;<a "
"href=\"http://www.chooseworkttw.net/about/index.html\">Ticket to "
"Work</a>&nbsp;program supports career development for Social Security disability "
"beneficiaries age 18 through 64 who want to work. The program is free and "
"voluntary.</li><li>The&nbsp;<a "
"href=\"http://www.abilityone.gov/\">AbilityOne.gov</a>&nbsp;program "
"provides&nbsp;<a "
"href=\"http://www.abilityone.gov/abilityone_network/employment.html\">employment "
"opportunities</a>&nbsp;with nonprofit agencies and community rehabilitation "
"programs across the country for people who are blind or who have other "
"significant disabilities.</li><li>The&nbsp;<a "
"href=\"http://www.opm.gov/policy-data-oversight/disability-employment/\">Disability "
"Employment</a>&nbsp;section of the Office of Personnel Management&nbsp;(OPM) "
"provides information on federal government hiring processes, reasonable "
"accommodations, and federal agency program coordinators who help hire and "
"accommodate employees with disabilities.&nbsp;</li><li><a "
"href=\"http://askjan.org/\">JAN, the Job Accommodation Network</a>, can answer "
"your questions about workplace accommodations and your rights under the <a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/laws-and-regulations#item-35762\">Americans with "
"Disabilities Act (ADA)</a>. It also <a "
"href=\"http://askjan.org/cgi-win/TypeQuery.exe?902\">lists state vocational "
"rehabilitation agencies</a> to help you discover employment "
"options.</li><li>NCWD/Youth provides&nbsp;<a "
"href=\"http://www.ncwd-youth.info/youth\">resources to help youth transition "
"from school to work</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a "
"href=\"http://www.ncwd-youth.info/youth-development\">youth development and "
"leadership opportunities and resources</a>.</li><li>The Campaign for Disability "
"Employment's <a "
"href=\"http://www.whatcanyoudocampaign.org/blog/index.php/what-can-you-do-resources/\">What "
"Can You Do?</a>&nbsp;website has job tips and resources for young people and "
"adults with disabilities, their family and educators, and "
"employers.&nbsp;</li></ul>"
msgstr ""

#: https://platform-api.usa.gov:443/api/v1/usagov/narratives/35787.json#title
msgid "Food Stamps (SNAP Food Benefits)"
msgstr ""

#: https://platform-api.usa.gov:443/api/v1/usagov/narratives/35787.json#summary
msgid "How to apply for SNAP food benefits, also known as food stamps."
msgstr ""

#: https://platform-api.usa.gov:443/api/v1/usagov/narratives/35787.json#html
msgid ""
"<h3>What help is available?</h3><p>If you have a low income, the <a "
"href=\"https://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/supplemental-nutrition-assistance-program-snap\">Supplemental "
"Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP)</a>, formerly known as \"food stamps,\" is a "
"federal nutrition program that can help you stretch your food budget.</p><h3>Am "
"I eligible?</h3><p>To determine if you are eligible, you must meet certain <a "
"href=\"https://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/eligibility\">requirements including "
"resource and income limits</a>.&nbsp;</p><h3>How do I apply?</h3><p>Find the <a "
"href=\"http://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/apply\">online application for your "
"state</a>, local office addresses, and phone numbers. You may &nbsp;also apply "
"in person at a state or local office.</p><h3>Is there anything else I need to "
"know?</h3><ul><li><p>You get benefits each month on a plastic electronic "
"benefits transfer (EBT) card, which you use like a credit or debit card to "
"purchase <a href=\"http://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/eligible-food-items\">eligible "
"food items</a> at your <a "
"href=\"https://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/retailerlocator\">local authorized SNAP "
"grocery stores and at some farmer’s markets</a>.</p></li><li><p>Some states have "
"<a href=\"http://www.fns.usda.gov/ebt/state-ebt-websites\">websites set up for "
"managing your benefits</a>. If your state doesn't have an EBT management "
"website, you can contact your <a "
"href=\"http://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/state-informationhotline-numbers\">state "
"SNAP office</a> to check your benefits.</p></li></ul><h3>How do I file a "
"complaint?</h3><p>If you need to file a complaint concerning your food stamps or "
"attempt to get food stamps, the following resources can help:</p><ul><li><p>If "
"you have <a "
"href=\"http://asktheexpert.custhelp.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/1595\">questions "
"about your benefit amount</a>, contact your <a "
"href=\"https://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/state-informationhotline-numbers\">local "
"field office</a> to request a hearing.</p></li><li><p>File a <a "
"href=\"http://www.usda.gov/oig/hotline.htm\">complaint online or by phone about "
"a SNAP retailer</a>. You will need to give the name and the location of the "
"store. You may remain anonymous if you choose.</p></li><li><p>If you suspect "
"fraud or abuse of the SNAP program, contact your <a "
"href=\"https://www.fns.usda.gov/report-nutrition-assistance-fraud-state\">state's "
"SNAP fraud hotline &nbsp;or website</a>.</p></li><li><p><a "
"href=\"https://www.ascr.usda.gov/node/119\">Learn how to file a complaint</a> if "
"you believe you have experienced discrimination in the SNAP program because of "
"age, sex, color, race, disability, religious creed, national origin, limited "
"English proficiency, or political beliefs.</p></li></ul><h3>For "
"Retailers</h3><p>If you are a retailer trying to become authorized to accept "
"SNAP benefits, <a href=\"https://www.fns.usda.gov/snap/retailer-apply\">follow "
"these application steps</a>.</p>"
msgstr ""

#: https://platform-api.usa.gov:443/api/v1/usagov/narratives/37562.json#title
msgid "How the U.S. Government Is Organized"
msgstr ""

#: https://platform-api.usa.gov:443/api/v1/usagov/narratives/37562.json#summary
msgid "Learn how the U.S. federal government is organized."
msgstr ""

#: https://platform-api.usa.gov:443/api/v1/usagov/narratives/37562.json#html
msgid ""
"<p>The <a "
"href=\"https://www.archives.gov/founding-docs/constitution\">Constitution of the "
"United States</a> divides the federal government into three branches to make "
"sure no individual or group will have too much "
"power:</p><ul><li>Legislative&mdash;Makes laws (Congress&mdash;House of "
"Representatives and Senate)</li><li>Executive&mdash;Carries out laws (President, "
"Vice President, Cabinet, most federal agencies)</li><li>Judicial&mdash;Evaluates "
"laws (Supreme Court and other courts)</li></ul><p>Each branch of government can "
"change acts of the other branches:</p><ul><li>The President can veto legislation "
"created by Congress and nominates heads of federal agencies.</li><li>Congress "
"confirms or rejects the President's nominees and can remove the President from "
"office in exceptional circumstances.</li><li>The Justices of the Supreme Court, "
"who can overturn unconstitutional laws, are nominated by the President and "
"confirmed by the Senate.</li></ul><p>This ability of each branch to respond to "
"the actions of the other branches is called the system of checks and "
"balances.</p><h3>Legislative Branch</h3><p>The legislative branch <a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/how-laws-are-made#item-35837\">drafts proposed "
"laws</a>, confirms or rejects Presidential nominations for heads of federal "
"agencies, federal judges, and the Supreme Court, and has the authority to "
"declare war. This branch includes Congress (the Senate and House of "
"Representatives) and <a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/legislative-agencies\">special agencies and "
"offices</a> that provide support services to Congress. American citizens have "
"the right to vote for Senators and Representatives through free, confidential "
"ballots.</p><ul><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.senate.gov/general/contact_information/senators_cfm.cfm\">Senate</a>&mdash;There "
"are two elected Senators per state, totaling 100 Senators. A Senate term is six "
"years and there is no limit to the number of terms an individual can "
"serve.</li><li><a href=\"https://www.house.gov/representatives\">House of "
"Representatives</a>&mdash;There are 435 elected Representatives, which are "
"divided among the 50 states in proportion to their total population. There are "
"additional non-voting delegates who represent the District of Columbia and the "
"territories. A Representative serves a two-year term, and there is no limit to "
"the number of terms an individual can serve.</li></ul><h3>Executive "
"Branch</h3><p>The <a "
"href=\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/about-the-white-house/the-executive-branch/\">executive "
"branch</a>&nbsp;carries out and enforces laws. It includes the President, Vice "
"President, the Cabinet, executive departments, independent agencies, and other "
"boards, commissions, and committees.</p><p>American citizens have the right to "
"vote for the President and Vice President through free, confidential "
"ballots.</p><p>Key roles of the executive branch include:</p><ul><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/people/donald-j-trump/\">President</a>&mdash;The "
"President leads the country. He or she is the head of state, leader of the "
"federal government, and Commander in Chief of the United States Armed Forces. "
"The President serves a four-year term and can be elected no more than two "
"times.</li><li><a href=\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/people/mike-pence/\">Vice "
"President</a>&mdash;The Vice President supports the President. If the President "
"is unable to serve, the Vice President becomes President. The Vice President can "
"be elected and serve an unlimited number of four-year terms as Vice President, "
"even under a different President.</li><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-trump-administration/the-cabinet/\">The "
"Cabinet</a>&mdash;Cabinet members serve as advisors to the President. They "
"include the Vice President, heads of executive departments, and other "
"high-ranking government officials. Cabinet members are nominated by the "
"President and must be approved by a simple majority of the Senate--51 votes if "
"all 100 Senators vote.</li></ul><h4>Executive Branch Agencies, Commissions, and "
"Committees</h4><p>Much of the work in the executive branch is done by federal "
"agencies, departments, committees, and other groups.</p><ul><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/executive-office-of-the-president\">Executive Office "
"of the President</a> &ndash; The Executive Office of the President communicates "
"the President’s message and deals with the federal budget, security, and other "
"high priorities.</li><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/executive-departments\">Executive Departments</a> "
"&ndash; These are the main agencies of the federal government. The heads of "
"these 15 agencies are also members of the President’s cabinet.<ul><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/sub-agencies\">Executive Department Sub-Agencies</a> "
"&ndash; Smaller sub-agencies support specialized work within their parent "
"executive department agencies.</li></ul></li><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/independent-agencies\">Independent Agencies</a> "
"&ndash; These agencies are not represented in the cabinet and are not part of "
"the Executive Office of the President. They deal with government operations, the "
"economy, and regulatory oversight.</li><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/boards-commissions-committees\">Boards, Commissions, "
"and Committees</a> &ndash; Congress or the President establish these smaller "
"organizations to manage specific tasks and areas that don’t fall under parent "
"agencies.</li><li><a href=\"https://www.usa.gov/quasi-official\">Quasi-Official "
"Agencies</a> &ndash; Although they’re not officially part of the executive "
"branch, these agencies are required by federal statute to release certain "
"information about their programs and activities in the <a "
"href=\"https://www.federalregister.gov/\">Federal Register, the daily journal of "
"government activities</a>.</li></ul><h3>Judicial Branch</h3><p>The <a "
"href=\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/about-the-white-house/the-judicial-branch/\">judicial "
"branch</a>&nbsp;interprets the meaning of laws, applies laws to individual "
"cases, and decides if laws violate the Constitution. It's comprised of the "
"Supreme Court and other federal courts.</p><ul><li><a "
"href=\"http://www.supremecourt.gov/\">Supreme Court</a>&mdash;The Supreme Court "
"is the highest court in the United States. The Justices of the Supreme Court are "
"nominated by the President and must be approved by the Senate.<ul><li><a "
"href=\"https://www.supremecourt.gov/about/justices.aspx\">Nine members</a> make "
"up the Supreme Court&mdash; a Chief Justice and eight Associate Justices. There "
"must be a minimum or quorum of <a "
"href=\"https://www.supremecourt.gov/about/faq_general.aspx\">six Justices</a> to "
"decide a case.</li><li>If there is an even number of Justices and a case results "
"in a tie, the lower court's decision stands.</li><li>There is no fixed term for "
"Justices. They serve until their death, retirement, or removal in exceptional "
"circumstances.</li><li>Learn more about <a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/supreme-court\">how the supreme court "
"works</a>.</li></ul></li><li><p><a "
"href=\"https://www.usa.gov/judicial-agencies\">Federal Courts and Judicial "
"Agencies</a> &ndash; The Constitution gives Congress the authority to establish "
"other <a href=\"http://www.uscourts.gov/about-federal-courts\">federal "
"courts</a> to handle cases that involve federal laws including tax and "
"bankruptcy, lawsuits involving U.S. and state governments or the Constitution, "
"and more. Other federal judicial agencies and programs support the courts and "
"research judicial policy.</p></li></ul><h4>Confirmation Process for Judges and "
"Justices</h4><p>Appointments for Supreme Court Justices and other federal "
"judgeships follow the same basic process:</p><ul><li>The President nominates a "
"person to fill a vacant judgeship.</li><li>The <a "
"href=\"https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/nominations\">Senate Judiciary "
"Committee</a> holds a hearing on the nominee and votes on whether to forward the "
"nomination to the full Senate.</li><li>If the nomination moves forward, the "
"Senate can debate the nomination. Debate must end before the Senate can vote on "
"whether to confirm the nominee. A Senator will request unanimous consent to end "
"the debate, but any Senator can refuse.</li><li>Without unanimous consent, the "
"Senate must pass a <a "
"href=\"https://www.senate.gov/reference/reference_index_subjects/Cloture_vrd.htm\">cloture "
"motion</a> to end the debate. It takes a simple majority of votes&mdash;51 if "
"all 100 Senators vote&mdash;to pass cloture and end debate about a federal "
"judicial nominee.</li><li>Once the debate ends, the Senate votes on "
"confirmation. The nominee for Supreme Court or any other federal judgeship needs "
"a simple majority of votes&mdash;51 if all 100 Senators vote&mdash;to be "
"confirmed.</li></ul>"
msgstr ""

